{
    "actions": [],
    "controlScriptCode": "/**\n * OBD-II Poller Control Loop (works with any OBD-II compliant vehicle)\n *\n * Talks to an ELM327-compatible adapter (e.g. OBDLink EX) plugged in as a\n * UART/serial source. setup() initializes the adapter once; loop() polls a\n * round-robin of mandatory Mode-01 PIDs: engine RPM (010C), vehicle speed\n * (010D), coolant temp (0105), calculated engine load (0104), intake air temp\n * (010F) and throttle position (0111), plus the adapter's own battery-voltage\n * reading (AT RV). Every request uses deviceWriteAndWait() to send and block\n * (on the worker thread, never the UI) until the ELM327 \">\" prompt marks the\n * end of the reply.\n *\n * No vehicle-specific tuning is required, but OBD-II does not require a car to\n * support every PID: the core three (RPM, speed, coolant) answer on essentially\n * any car, while load, intake air temp and throttle are common but not\n * universal. AT RV always works (the adapter measures it). For an unsupported\n * PID the adapter returns \"NO DATA\", dataBytes() comes back empty, the byte\n * count falls short of the job's required `bytes` and the tableSet() is\n * skipped, so that gauge reads \"No data\" and the others keep working.\n *\n * The reply is decoded right here and written into the \"OBD\" data table with\n * tableSet(). dashboardTick() then forces the gauges (virtual datasets whose\n * transforms read the table) to render. Nothing needs a frame parser, and\n * the dashboard updates even though the adapter only speaks when spoken to.\n *\n * Note: this table-driven pattern updates the dashboard and, when an export\n * sink is enabled, records to it too: dashboardTick() fans the synthesized\n * frame out to CSV/MDF4/Session-database/MQTT/API just like a real device\n * frame, so the decoded gauges can be logged without a frame parser.\n *\n * ELM327 protocol reference (commands are ASCII hex + CR, replies are ASCII\n * hex text terminated by the \">\" prompt): see the ELM327 datasheet at\n * https://cdn.sparkfun.com/assets/learn_tutorials/8/3/ELM327DS.pdf\n */\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// Configuration & constants\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n// Round-robin list of {register, pid, bytes, decode} jobs.\n//   reg    - column written in the \"OBD\" table\n//   pid    - Mode-01 request, ASCII hex (the adapter wants this + CR)\n//   bytes  - minimum data bytes the decode needs; a shorter reply is skipped\n//   decode - turns the data bytes into the engineering value\nconst JOBS = [{\n        reg: \"rpm\",\n        pid: \"010C\",\n        bytes: 2,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return (b[0] * 256 + b[1]) / 4;\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        reg: \"speed\",\n        pid: \"010D\",\n        bytes: 1,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return b[0];\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        reg: \"coolant\",\n        pid: \"0105\",\n        bytes: 1,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return b[0] - 40;\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        reg: \"load\",\n        pid: \"0104\",\n        bytes: 1,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return (b[0] * 100) / 255;\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        reg: \"intake\",\n        pid: \"010F\",\n        bytes: 1,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return b[0] - 40;\n        }\n    },\n    {\n        reg: \"throttle\",\n        pid: \"0111\",\n        bytes: 1,\n        decode: function(b) {\n            return (b[0] * 100) / 255;\n        }\n    }\n];\n\n// Mode-01 positive responses echo the request mode + 0x40, i.e. \"41\" + pid.\nconst MODE01_REPLY_PREFIX = \"41\";\n\n// ELM327 ends every reply with this prompt character.\nconst PROMPT = \">\";\n\n// Per-request reply budget. A real reply returns the instant the \">\" prompt\n// arrives, so this only bounds the wait for \"NO DATA\"/unsupported PIDs. It must\n// still outlast a slow reply: timing out mid-reply lets the next command\n// interrupt the adapter (\"STOPPED\") and shifts every reply by one. 400 ms is\n// well past a settled-bus answer yet keeps unsupported PIDs from stalling.\nconst REPLY_TIMEOUT_MS = 400;\n\n// Source the adapter is connected to. 0 is the primary device.\nconst ADAPTER_SOURCE = 0;\n\n// One AT RV (battery voltage) read every this many PID polls. Voltage barely\n// changes, so it need not refresh as often as the engine PIDs.\nconst VOLTAGE_EVERY = 6;\n\n// Wrap pollCount here so it never grows unbounded.\nconst POLL_COUNT_WRAP = 1000000;\n\n// Idle between polls so the worker thread yields. deviceWriteAndWait() already\n// blocks on the worker thread, so this only needs to be a brief yield; a large\n// delay just throttles the refresh rate. Milliseconds.\nconst LOOP_DELAY_MS = 15;\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// Mutable state\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nlet jobIndex = 0;\nlet pollCount = 0;\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// ELM327 I/O\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n/**\n * @brief Sends one command and returns the ELM327 reply text (without the\n *        prompt), or \"\" on timeout. Waits for the \">\" prompt terminator.\n */\nfunction ask(cmd, timeoutMs) {\n    const r = deviceWriteAndWait(cmd + \"\\r\", timeoutMs, PROMPT, ADAPTER_SOURCE);\n    return (r && r.ok) ? r.data : \"\";\n}\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// Reply parsing\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n/**\n * @brief Parses an ELM327 reply (\"410C1AF8\") into its data bytes after the\n *        mode+pid header. Returns [] for \"NO DATA\" / \"SEARCHING...\" / noise.\n *        `pid` is the bare two-byte PID, e.g. \"0C\" for request \"010C\".\n */\nfunction dataBytes(reply, pid) {\n    const clean = reply.replace(/[^0-9A-Fa-f]/g, \"\").toUpperCase();\n    const head = MODE01_REPLY_PREFIX + pid;\n    const at = clean.indexOf(head);\n    if (at < 0)\n        return [];\n\n    const body = clean.substr(at + head.length);\n    const bytes = [];\n    for (let i = 0; i + 1 < body.length; i += 2)\n        bytes.push(parseInt(body.substr(i, 2), 16));\n\n    return bytes;\n}\n\n/**\n * @brief Parses an AT RV reply (\"12.6V\") into a number, or NaN when the adapter\n *        returns no usable voltage. AT RV has no 41xx header; it is not a PID.\n */\nfunction voltsFromReply(reply) {\n    const m = reply.match(/-?\\d+(\\.\\d+)?/);\n    return m ? parseFloat(m[0]) : NaN;\n}\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// Lifecycle: setup\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n/**\n * @brief One-time adapter initialization: reset, disable echo/linefeeds/spaces\n *        so replies are compact, and select automatic protocol detection so the\n *        same script works on CAN, ISO and PWM vehicles alike.\n */\nfunction setup() {\n    ask(\"ATZ\", 1500);  // reset (slow; adapter reboots)\n    ask(\"ATE0\", 400);  // echo off\n    ask(\"ATL0\", 400);  // linefeeds off\n    ask(\"ATS0\", 400);  // spaces off\n    ask(\"ATSP0\", 400); // protocol = auto\n    for (let tries = 0; tries < 4; ++tries) {\n        if (dataBytes(ask(\"0100\", 8000), \"00\").length > 0)\n            break;\n    }\n    notifyInfo(\"OBD-II\", \"Adapter initialized; polling engine telemetry.\");\n}\n\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n// Lifecycle: loop\n//------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\n/**\n * @brief Polls the next PID, decodes the reply and writes the \"OBD\" table.\n *        Every VOLTAGE_EVERY polls it also reads battery voltage via AT RV,\n *        then ticks the dashboard so the gauges render the fresh values.\n */\nfunction loop() {\n    const job = JOBS[jobIndex];\n    jobIndex = (jobIndex + 1) % JOBS.length;\n\n    const b = dataBytes(ask(job.pid, REPLY_TIMEOUT_MS), job.pid.substr(2));\n    if (b.length >= job.bytes)\n        tableSet(\"OBD\", job.reg, job.decode(b));\n\n    if ((pollCount % VOLTAGE_EVERY) === 0) {\n        const v = voltsFromReply(ask(\"ATRV\", REPLY_TIMEOUT_MS));\n        if (!isNaN(v))\n            tableSet(\"OBD\", \"voltage\", v);\n    }\n\n    pollCount = (pollCount + 1) % POLL_COUNT_WRAP;\n    dashboardTick();\n    delay(LOOP_DELAY_MS);\n}",
    "customizeWorkspaces": true,
